Built-in Markers
These are already provided by pytest (no need to define)

Common Built-in Markers
->@pytest.mark.skip
Skips the test

-> @pytest.mark.skipif
@pytest.mark.skipif(condition, reason="message")
Skips based on condition
used to conditionally skip a test based on a boolean expression. If the condition evaluates to True, the test is skipped with a given reason

->@pytest.mark.xfail
Expected to fail

-> @pytest.mark.parametrize
run the same test multiple times with different inputs
Instead of writing multiple test functions, you write one test + multiple data sets
Run test multiple times with different data
syntax:
@pytest.mark.parametrize("arg1,arg2,...", [(val1,val2), (val3,val4)])
def test_function(arg1, arg2):
    ...


@pytest.fixture
@pytest.fixture is used in pytest to create reusable setup code for your tests.
It helps you:\
Avoid repeating setup code
Manage test dependencies
Keep tests clean and readable
A fixture is a function that runs before a test and provides data or setup to that test.



